SIMPLE: tongue
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Tongue
<hw>Tongue</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>tunge</ets>,
<ets>tonge</ets>, AS. <ets>tunge</ets>; akin to OFries.
<ets>tunge</ets>, D. <ets>tong</ets>, OS. <ets>tunga</ets>, G.
<ets>zunge</ets>, OHG. <ets>zunga</ets>, Icel. & Sw. <ets>tunga</ets>,
Dan <ets>tunge</ets>, Goth. <ets>tugg⟦omac⟧</ets>, OL.
<ets>dingua</ets>, L. <ets>lingua</ets>. ⟦root⟧243 Cf.<er>Language</er>,
<er>Lingo</er>. ]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>an organ situated in the floor of
the mouth of most vertebrates and connected with the hyoid
arch.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The tongue is usually muscular, mobile, and free at one
extremity, and in man other mammals is the principal organ of taste,
aids in the prehension of food, in swallowing, and in modifying the
voice as in speech.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To make his English sweet upon his <qex>tongue</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The power of articulate utterance; speech.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Parrots imitating human <qex>tongue</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Discourse; fluency of speech or
expression.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Much <qex>tongue</qex> and much judgment seldom go together.</q>
<rj><qau>L. Estrange.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Honorable discourse; eulogy.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She was born noble; let that title find her a private grave, but
neither <qex>tongue</qex> nor honor.</q> <rj><qau>Beau. &
Fl.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A language; the whole sum of words used by a
particular nation; <as>as, the English <ex>tongue</ex></as>.</def>
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whose <qex>tongue</qex> thou shalt not understand.</q>
<rj><qau>Deut. xxviii. 49.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To speak all <qex>tongues</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Speech; words or declarations only; -- opposed to
<xex>thoughts</xex> or <xex>actions</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My little children, let us love in word, neither in
<qex>tongue</qex>, but in deed and in truth.</q> <rj><qau>1 John iii.
18.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>A people having a distinct language.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A will gather all nations and <qex>tongues</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Isa. lxvi. 18.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The lingual ribbon,
or odontophore, of a mollusk.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The proboscis of a
moth or a butterfly.</def> <sd>(c)</sd> <def>The lingua of an
insect.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any small sole.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <def>That which is considered as resembing an animal's
tongue, in position or form.</def> Specifically: --⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(a)</sd> <def>A projection, or slender appendage or fixture; as,
the <xex>tongue</xex> of a buckle, or of a balance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1517 -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <def>A projection on the side, as of a board, which fits
into a groove.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(c)</sd> <def>A point, or long, narrow strip of land, projecting
from the mainland into a sea or a lake.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(d)</sd> <def>The pole of a vehicle; especially, the pole of an
ox cart, to the end of which the oxen are yoked.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(e)</sd> <def>The clapper of a bell.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(f)</sd> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>A short piece of rope spliced
into the upper part of standing backstays, etc.; also. the upper main
piece of a mast composed of several pieces.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(g)</sd> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>Same as <er>Reed</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>, 5.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To hold the tongue</b></col>, <cd>to be silent.</cd> --
<col><b>Tongue bone</b></col> <fld>(Anat.)</fld>, <cd>the hyoid
bone.</cd> -- <col><b>Tongue grafting</b></col>. <cd>See under
<er>Grafting</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Language; speech; expression. See
<er>Language</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tongue</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Tongue
<hw>Tongue</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Tongued</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Tonguing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To speak; to
utter.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Such stuff as madmen <xex>tongue</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To chide; to scold.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>How might she <qex>tongue</qex> me.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>To modulate or modify with the
tongue, as notes, in playing the flute and some other wind
instruments.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To join means of a tongue and grove; <as>as, to
<ex>tongue</ex> boards together</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tongue</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Tongue
<hw>Tongue</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To talk; to
prate.</def> <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>To use the tongue in forming the
notes, as in playing the flute and some other wind
instruments.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tonguebird</ent>⟦br⟧
